WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:03.620
Hi, I'm Glen.

00:00:03.670 --> 00:00:06.620
I'm going to talk to you about Oak Log, which

00:00:06.700 --> 00:00:10.630
is a cooperative experiment that we've started in the Oakland area

00:00:10.650 --> 00:00:14.800
to build a community calendar, so a kind of commons

00:00:14.810 --> 00:00:17.920
for event data.

00:00:17.960 --> 00:00:21.200
And for a little context for approach, I have some scar

00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:24.840
tissue from crypto, and so one of the things that I

00:00:25.050 --> 00:00:28.140
really like this term sewer socialism, and I think Zor

00:00:28.140 --> 00:00:30.830
an in New York is one of the folks that exemplifies

00:00:30.830 --> 00:00:33.770
this, which is you win someone's trust over through an

00:00:33.770 --> 00:00:35.260
outcome rather than ideology.

00:00:35.260 --> 00:00:37.990
So I think as we've gone through this project, even

00:00:37.990 --> 00:00:40.790
though I think about it as like digital public media infrastructure,

00:00:40.790 --> 00:00:43.420
I try to really ground it in we are helping Oaklanders

00:00:43.420 --> 00:00:46.340
and other Bay Area folk find and go to local events,

00:00:46.350 --> 00:00:49.560
and we happen to be using that protocol.

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:52.340
This all starts with the Oakland Review of Books, which is

00:00:52.340 --> 00:00:56.730
a new alt weekly that helped start last year.

00:00:56.760 --> 00:00:58.330
And as part of the Oakland Review of books, we started

00:00:58.330 --> 00:01:03.160
to publish a community calendar of literary events, of cultural events

00:01:03.180 --> 00:01:06.180
, of protests, and it got some real great pickup.

00:01:06.180 --> 00:01:07.900
And so one of the things I saw, this is Mart

00:01:07.990 --> 00:01:10.040
ina, who does a lot of this work for us,

00:01:10.090 --> 00:01:12.350
and it was a huge pain for her to do this work

00:01:12.370 --> 00:01:12.760
.

00:01:12.830 --> 00:01:15.660
All of these events are fragmented all over the place,

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:17.890
so getting all that data in one place was a real pain

00:01:17.890 --> 00:01:18.060
.

00:01:18.060 --> 00:01:20.240
And then the part that she actually really liked to do that

00:01:20.270 --> 00:01:23.720
was also really valuable for our audience, which is that cur

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:26.890
ation, the taste, telling people why that this might be

00:01:26.890 --> 00:01:29.220
an interesting thing to go to.

00:01:29.230 --> 00:01:31.980
And that was a tiny portion of the work that she actually

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:32.640
got to do.

00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:36.870
So we built some tools, Discord bot and some other CMS

00:01:37.040 --> 00:01:40.640
tools just to help us manage this.

00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:43.080
And one of the things we started realizing as we talked to

00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:45.450
lots of other people around the Bay is that there's there

00:01:45.540 --> 00:01:47.890
's tons, there's dozens of folks that are doing the

00:01:48.050 --> 00:01:51.450
same thing, the same putting together these kind of curated calend

00:01:51.450 --> 00:01:51.640
ars.

00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:54.880
And so what we decided to do is just get them all

00:01:54.930 --> 00:01:56.100
in one room.

00:01:56.100 --> 00:02:00.150
So we invited all of the folks, the public media station

00:02:00.250 --> 00:02:04.340
, the neighborhood calendar makers, there's lots of folks,

00:02:04.340 --> 00:02:07.030
alt weeklies, newsrooms, all that are doing the

00:02:07.260 --> 00:02:10.280
same thing of managing calendars and helping people find events.

00:02:10.280 --> 00:02:14.290
So we got everybody together and we talked about how might we

00:02:14.380 --> 00:02:17.160
share practices, share tools, share data, what would that

00:02:17.170 --> 00:02:17.930
look like?

00:02:17.930 --> 00:02:21.010
And one thing that came out of that is everyone had the

00:02:21.010 --> 00:02:23.700
same sense of how do we do this thing together?

00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:25.360
We need a mega calendar, but but not dystopian

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:25.570
.

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:28.860
And so we can just do things.

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:32.410
And so we started to talk about what it might look like

00:02:32.410 --> 00:02:34.400
to do this together on an open protocol.

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:38.380
And so we kind of walked through and I think those are

00:02:38.380 --> 00:02:40.410
some of the lessons of how we've talked about this is

00:02:40.410 --> 00:02:42.980
, so you know, starting with something like on Instagram re

00:02:42.980 --> 00:02:45.740
els, where you have a venue publishing their data in this

00:02:45.740 --> 00:02:49.520
form, we've moved that out now into a database that

00:02:49.540 --> 00:02:51.990
each of our individual organizations are using, whether it's Gr

00:02:52.130 --> 00:02:53.500
ist or Airtable or Excel, what have you.

00:02:53.500 --> 00:02:56.660
And the next step is, can we do this in a

00:02:56.670 --> 00:02:57.700
shared database?

00:02:57.700 --> 00:03:00.670
Then, you know, here's the at proto record of

00:03:00.670 --> 00:03:02.240
a calendar event.

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:05.480
And so, you know, one of the helpful points here

00:03:05.480 --> 00:03:07.170
is, you know, can you start wherever you get your

00:03:07.170 --> 00:03:09.760
events, much like wherever you get to your podcasts, and

00:03:09.770 --> 00:03:13.530
actually have that event data that venues want out there anyways,

00:03:13.530 --> 00:03:14.810
actually be available.

00:03:14.920 --> 00:03:17.630
And then there's a lot more we can start doing with

00:03:17.630 --> 00:03:18.100
it.

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:21.400
And some of the advantages that were really attractive to the publishers

00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:24.520
is one is how do we start sharing these workflow tools.

00:03:24.620 --> 00:03:26.780
So we have our discord bot, there are others who have

00:03:26.780 --> 00:03:30.100
been building tools that are scraping venue sites or big event sites

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:32.640
, and tons of folks where it's just how does the

00:03:32.730 --> 00:03:36.690
venue actually create their own event or submit it to publishers,

00:03:36.690 --> 00:03:39.560
all going into the same lexicon, the same data

00:03:39.560 --> 00:03:40.900
that we can then use.

00:03:40.910 --> 00:03:44.200
And on the other end, we start being able to do

00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:47.760
a lot more with that data now that we've all collaborated

00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:49.460
on that shared element.

00:03:49.460 --> 00:03:52.570
So one is we can still maintain editorial control, we can

00:03:52.570 --> 00:03:57.560
still curate what is showing up in our individual publications and

00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:00.890
the commentary that we put around it, but we can also

00:04:00.890 --> 00:04:01.790
collaborate.

00:04:01.790 --> 00:04:03.680
So if we add an event, then Coyote,

00:04:03.680 --> 00:04:06.150
you know, if Orb adds something, and Coyote

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:08.990
, your same page SF can use that same, that same

00:04:09.040 --> 00:04:12.240
data, we can play with whatever format we like, whether

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:14.090
it's in a post or in a calendar, and really

00:04:14.150 --> 00:04:17.720
excited to start exploring more of the social functionality of can we

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:21.430
can we see what folks in your social network are interested in

00:04:21.430 --> 00:04:24.160
attending or going and not have it be specific to Luma

00:04:24.230 --> 00:04:26.540
or Eventbrite or others, I think it starts getting

00:04:26.560 --> 00:04:28.970
much more attractive from the user perspective.

00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:33.400
So focusing a little bit more on the publisher control piece,

00:04:33.470 --> 00:04:36.640
so we can still publish as we do in a newsletter.

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:39.870
But I think there's some other interesting examples here.

00:04:39.870 --> 00:04:42.770
This middle one is from Roundabout at New Public.

00:04:42.770 --> 00:04:45.430
And one of the things that they're really focused on is

00:04:45.430 --> 00:04:48.850
how do you moderate, you know, have a local neighborhood

00:04:48.970 --> 00:04:51.940
steward actually be able to moderate what goes on there.

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:54.300
I think they're using the same, same schema that we

00:04:54.300 --> 00:04:56.500
are, I think there's going to be some really interesting

00:04:56.500 --> 00:04:57.820
ways to interoperate there.

00:04:57.820 --> 00:05:01.810
Another really interesting example, this is a group down in the

00:05:01.810 --> 00:05:04.120
Bay called the relational tech project.

00:05:04.130 --> 00:05:08.500
And what they're doing is enabling neighborhood stewards to use AI

00:05:08.500 --> 00:05:12.980
tools to build their own applications, including things like calendar apps

00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:13.140
.

00:05:13.140 --> 00:05:15.650
And so and allow that to be much more situated and kind

00:05:15.650 --> 00:05:17.400
of fit for what that community needs.

00:05:17.400 --> 00:05:19.410
So, you know, the community of the outer sunset,

00:05:19.420 --> 00:05:22.260
for instance, in San Francisco also wants to see, you

00:05:22.260 --> 00:05:24.530
know, how the waves are, for instance, and incorporate

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:26.060
things that make sense for that community.

00:05:26.070 --> 00:05:31.810
So what's next from here is after our community calendar conference

00:05:31.930 --> 00:05:35.260
, we had not only a bunch of these media organizations excited

00:05:35.260 --> 00:05:37.060
, we have a bunch of people who really want to collaborate

00:05:37.080 --> 00:05:38.590
on the tech side.

00:05:38.590 --> 00:05:41.560
And one in particular, it's really interesting is KQ

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:44.280
ED, which is our big local NPR station that is

00:05:44.290 --> 00:05:46.710
really interested in anchoring and supporting this.

00:05:46.710 --> 00:05:49.000
And so we're starting to go down the path of what

00:05:49.090 --> 00:05:51.410
might it look like to create a community PDS for the

00:05:51.410 --> 00:05:55.280
Oakland Bay Area and specifically starting with with events.

00:05:55.280 --> 00:05:59.760
We're also starting to explore new local applications that actually take

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:02.090
advantage of this collaboration.

00:06:02.090 --> 00:06:05.970
So one organization is thinking about doing a pop up calendar that

00:06:05.970 --> 00:06:08.690
's kind of poorly suited for existing things like Yelp and

00:06:08.690 --> 00:06:09.140
others.

00:06:09.240 --> 00:06:10.900
So that's one thing we're looking into.

00:06:10.960 --> 00:06:13.440
Others are things more like a TV guide-ish, like

00:06:13.440 --> 00:06:15.600
what's happening right now in Oakland, the Bay Area.

00:06:15.610 --> 00:06:17.360
So I think there's going to be a lot of things

00:06:17.360 --> 00:06:18.840
that we can start building on top of this.

00:06:19.030 --> 00:06:23.380
We're starting with the media curators that are already trusted

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:26.110
, that already have audience, that already have attention.

00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:28.870
But from there, we're really excited to expand that participation

00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:31.720
and get more venues involved and ultimately more residents.

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:35.730
And then we're also looking at beyond what this group can

00:06:35.730 --> 00:06:39.410
do together just on events, but thinking more generally about what

00:06:39.550 --> 00:06:41.410
does the local community API look like?

00:06:41.450 --> 00:06:43.980
What is all the public data that we could could share?

00:06:43.980 --> 00:06:47.270
I think there's lots of other use cases of things like

00:06:47.270 --> 00:06:50.880
buy nothing groups or lending libraries or, you know, lots

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:53.990
of things that exist on kind of the margins of existing social

00:06:53.990 --> 00:06:57.180
platforms that if we had more of a public spectrum for the

00:06:57.180 --> 00:07:00.880
open social web, we can see really different applications develop.

00:07:00.880 --> 00:07:03.970
Much like in the US, the kind of content you see

00:07:03.970 --> 00:07:06.630
on PBS or NPR is quite a bit different than the

00:07:06.690 --> 00:07:07.660
way you see commercially.

00:07:07.670 --> 00:07:11.630
And then ideally, this all feeds into, hey, if

00:07:11.630 --> 00:07:15.020
this works in Oakland in the Bay Area and works for this

00:07:15.030 --> 00:07:17.770
NPR station or this Alt Weekly, how do we create

00:07:17.800 --> 00:07:21.720
this playbook that allows other geographies to do similar things

00:07:21.720 --> 00:07:23.150
of building for themselves?

00:07:23.150 --> 00:07:25.060
Yeah, so that's where we are.

00:07:25.060 --> 00:07:27.560
It's all kind of emergent, but I think what

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:30.620
I really love about it is it feels like a great demonstration

00:07:30.620 --> 00:07:34.150
of what I think is the promise of these applications on that

00:07:34.150 --> 00:07:37.780
protocol, which is really by collaborating across organization, can we

00:07:37.780 --> 00:07:41.160
actually build something that has a better experience for the users?

00:07:41.170 --> 00:07:43.570
You don't need to know anything about how this is built

00:07:43.810 --> 00:07:47.010
other than everybody has collaborated to make it better, and that

00:07:47.010 --> 00:07:48.010
's what you see.

00:07:48.010 --> 00:07:51.260
And so we can just do things together is the point.

00:07:51.260 --> 00:07:55.260
So let's hope on.
